        "subject": "LU-3970 ldlm: Add parallel drop_caches proc interface",
        "message": "LU-3970 ldlm: Add parallel drop_caches proc interface\n\nAdded a proc interface at /proc/fs/lustre/ldlm/drop_caches which\nclears lustre caches for all namespaces in parallel by spawning\nthreads to work on a queue of namespaces.  It only adds to the work\nqueue namespaces which are in the active list because those are the\nonly ones which should have any locks.  The proc interface is\nwrite-only and is used as follows:\n\necho 1 > /proc/fs/lustre/ldlm/drop_caches\n\nThe algorithm used by the new drop_caches interface is as follows.\nWhen drop_caches is written to, ldlm_drop_caches is called.  That\nfunction calls ldlm_dc_get_workq to get a work queue of work items\ncontaining namespaces to be cleared.  ldlm_dc_get_workq copies the\ncurrent list of active namespaces in the workq so that the\nldlm_namespace_lock can be held as briefly as possible.  Then\nldlm_drop_caches spawns a number of threads based on the number of\nCPUs.  Each thread accesses the workq, so access to the workq is\nsynchronized with an atomic counter in ldlm_dc_get_work_item.  When a\nthread gets a work item, it clears the associated namespace using\nldlm_ns_drop_cache.  Once all the work items have been processed, the\nthreads return.  ldlm_drop_caches then cleans up and returns. Any\nerrors encountered are returned by the proc interface.\n\nIn addition, the code from lprocfs_lru_size_seq_write which clears the\ncaches when \"clear\" is written to lru_size was moved into the function\nldlm_ns_drop_cache.  This was done because the same logic is needed by\nthe cache clearing threads.\n\nTwo tests, test_124c and test_124d, were written to test the two\ndifferent ways of clearing lustre caches.  Each test creates many\nfiles and then each clears lustre caches.  test_124c clears caches\nserially by writing \"clear\" to each namespace's lru_size interface.\ntest_124d clears caches in parallel across namespaces by writing \"1\"\nto /proc/fs/lustre/ldlm/drop_caches.  After clearing caches, each test\nthen checks that the number of unused locks is zero.\n\nSigned-off-by: Ryan Haasken <haasken@cray.com>\nChange-Id: I32fab3bf8526faf320db629b17e05df2f49a1750\n"
      },
